I think [Literal substitutions][1] work well for expressions like that.  For example:

    &lt;div class=&quot;banner_w3lspvt&quot; th:style=&quot;|background: url(/uploads/${dashboard.dashboard_photo});|&quot;&gt;


  [1]: https://www.thymeleaf.org/doc/tutorials/3.0/usingthymeleaf.html#literal-substitutions

Object spread [only copies](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Spread_syntax#Spread_in_object_literals) *enumerable own* properties:

&gt;It copies own enumerable properties from a provided object onto a new object.

With

```
class Person {
    constructor(name) { 
        this.name = name;
    }
    testFunction() {

    }
}

```

the `testFunction` is on `Person.prototype`, not on a Person instance, so it doesn&#39;t get copied; it&#39;s not an *own property*.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    class Person {
        constructor(name) { 
            this.name = name;
        }
        testFunction() {

        }
    }
    let personA = new Person(&quot;Tom&quot;);

    console.log(Person.prototype.hasOwnProperty(&#39;testFunction&#39;));
    console.log(personA.hasOwnProperty(&#39;testFunction&#39;));

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

If you assign `testFunction` to the instance in the constructor, it&#39;ll get copied:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    class Person {
      constructor(name) {
        this.name = name;
        this.testFunction = this.testFunction;
      }
      testFunction() {

      }
    }
    let personA = new Person(&quot;Tom&quot;);
    console.log(personA.hasOwnProperty(&#39;testFunction&#39;));
    let newArray = [];
    newArray.push({ ...personA });
    console.log(newArray);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The name is part of the class when initializing the constructor as this

    constructor(name) { 
        this.name=name
    }

When want to create an instance of the class it should be added the name as you want to same the object you should add the function in the constructor.
If you want the same shape add object it should add the function inside  the constructor:

    constructor(name) { 
